ðŸ”‘ 1. Administrative Distance (AD)

ðŸ‘‰ Definition: Router ke paas agar ek same destination ke liye multiple routes aa gaye (via different routing protocols), to priority kaise decide karega?
Ye kaam karta hai AD (Administrative Distance).

        AD = Trust level of a route (0â€“255)
        
        Lower AD = More trusted

ðŸ“Œ Example:
Maan le tujhe Delhi jaana hai.

        Papa bolte hai "Ye rasta best hai" (Static Route)
        
        Dost bolta hai "Google Maps ka rasta le" (OSPF)
        
        Padosi bolta hai "RIP ka rasta le"

Ab tu kiske upar jyada trust karega?

        Papa ki baat (AD 1) â†’ sabse trusted.
        
        Dost ki baat (AD 110) â†’ theek hai.
        
        Padosi ki baat (AD 120) â†’ least trusted.

âœ… Default AD Values:

        | Routing Source     | AD Value | Trust Level     |
        | ------------------ | -------- | --------------- |
        | Directly Connected | 0        | Most trusted    |
        | Static Route       | 1        | Very high trust |
        | EIGRP (Internal)   | 90       | Trusted         |
        | OSPF               | 110      | Medium trust    |
        | RIP                | 120      | Less trusted    |
        | External EIGRP     | 170      | Lower trust     |
        | Unknown / Invalid  | 255      | Never trusted   |

ðŸ”‘ 2. Hop Count

ðŸ‘‰ Definition: Hop = Ek router se dusre router tak ek jump.
Hop count = destination tak pahunchne ke liye kitne routers cross karne padhe.

        RIP routing protocol uses Hop Count as its metric.
        
        Lower hop count = Better path.

ðŸ“Œ Example:
        Tu Mumbai se Pune ja raha hai.
        
        Route 1: 2 signals (2 hops) â†’ short.
        
        Route 2: 5 signals (5 hops) â†’ long.
        Router hamesha 2 hop wala path choose karega.

âš¡ Limitation:

        RIP me max hop count = 15 hops (16 = unreachable).

ðŸŽ¯ Quick Summary (Shortcut)

Administrative Distance (AD): Which route to trust if multiple available. (Lower is better)

Hop Count: How many routers to cross before reaching destination. (Fewer is better)
